hands_on_practices.problem:
An individual is a carrier of a balanced Robertsonian translocation, a common type of chromosomal rearrangement in humans. This translocation involves the fusion of the long arms of two acrocentric chromosomes, in this case, chromosome 13 and chromosome 14. Consequently, this individual has a total of 45 chromosomes in their somatic cells, including one normal chromosome 13, one normal chromosome 14, and one large derivative chromosome formed by the fusion of chromosomes 13 and 14.

For the purpose of this problem, let's use the following notation for the genetic material relevant to gamete formation:
- `$N_{13}$`: A normal chromosome 13
- `$N_{14}$`: A normal chromosome 14
- `$T(13;14)$`: The translocated derivative chromosome containing the long arms of both chromosome 13 and chromosome 14.

During prophase I of meiosis in this individual, the two normal chromosomes and the one derivative chromosome pair up to form a trivalent structure. Segregation of these three chromosomes occurs during anaphase I.

Assuming all possible segregation patterns of this trivalent are equally likely, which of the following sets correctly lists all six distinct types of gametes that can be theoretically produced by this individual with respect to these specific chromosomes?

A. {$N_{13}$, $N_{14}$}, {$T(13;14)$}, {$N_{13}$}, {$N_{14}$}, {$N_{13}$, $T(13;14)$}, {$N_{14}$, $T(13;14)$}

B. {$N_{13}$, $N_{14}$}, {$T(13;14)$}, {$N_{13}$}, {$N_{14}$}

C. {$N_{13}$, $N_{14}$}, {$T(13;14)$}

D. {$N_{13}$}, {$N_{14}$}, {$T(13;14)$}, {$N_{13}$, $T(13;14)$}, {$N_{14}$, $T(13;14)$}

E. {$N_{13}$, $N_{14}$}, {$T(13;14)$}, {$N_{13}$, $N_{14}$, $T(13;14)$}
